<font color="#FF0000">THE MIRACLES OF WAR</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct  2 11:36:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW,<br><br>
I've never regreted or have ever asked for forgiveness for what I did in Vietnam. Guess I've always looked at it as a just war and have no regrets for what ever I accomplished there. Have never felt God needed to forgive me for anything I did there. Now, on the police department that's a different story. <br><br>
I belief we are all a bit cautious in speaking about our religious beliefs because of today's social atmosphere that dictates it is not politically correct to share from our faith because we might offend someone. <br><br>
As many times that I was spared in Vietnam it wasn't until recently that I realized just how powerful that protection was. While I had always given God the credit for some of the more obvious incidents, it wasn't until I read the Marine Corps historical accounts of those events as well as heard how others described what occurred that I realized I had not given God proper credit for sparing me during some of the most fierce fire fights where I was (unknown to me at that time), the enemy's primary target and should have been killed many times over.  Why was I spared?<br><br>
Is there a destiny we all must fulfill? I believed I have fulfilled mine, many times over and have all too often taken on the duties others failed to do. I'm not complaining, I realize that it's a blessing to be able to help others but I don't like to take any duties that they could have done themselves.<br><br>
ADDITONAL READING FOR THOSE COURIOUS ABOUT DIVINE INTERVENTION IN VIETNAM FOLLOWS, (Not for the faint hearted).<br><br>
One memorable incident , regarding divine intervention that sticks boldly in my mind. I've enclosed it below for those of you that might find situations like that interesting.<br><br>
There are many stories we've all heard about men and war, about soldiers returning home from war and incidents that occurred that could not be explained by national sources. Private moments when some unknown force, a chance or divine encounter occurred that intervened in their behalf and their lives were spared. What occurred would erase any doubts there may have been lingering in my mind concerning the existence of divine beings. It not only made me a confirmed believer that there is a supreme being but I also realized that He does intervene in the affairs of men. I was not a religious men, certainly I was not clean in God's eye. Only He knew how many of the enemy I had blindly shot at and had wounded or killed. The Lord's prayer, continued to be the only prayer I knew. Once while standing watch in the darkness one night, I had spent a lengthy period of time trying to dissect, trying to fully understand what the words in that prayer meant. I had only gone to religious services a couple of times since my arrival in Viet Nam.<br><br>
We were running a battalion size operation in Dodge City, Charles Robb was our CO, that morning I was walking point for the company.<br><br>
From Dreams of Glory © copyright 1997, Cook Barela<br><br>
RETURN TO DODGE CITY<br>
South Viet Nam<br>
10:30 hours April 3rd, 1968<br>
Aggie was carrying the gun and James was his A-gunner. The lieutenant assigned me to second squad. It wasn't the usual practice but perhaps he felt that since I kept opening up on the enemy I would be more likely to see them before others or perhaps it had something to do with having shot out the legs of the women running with the two VC's in the village. I knew that I had irritated the lieutenant with my aggressiveness and he seemed determined to teach me a lesson and so I found myself walking point for the platoon with the rest of the company bringing up the rear. <br><br>
In the Marine  Corps you had been taught to keep our distance from each other and not to bunch up especially while out on patrol.  Because of booby traps and the way ambushes were set up in Viet Nam's dense forrest, the recommended 5' distance, was extended to 20-30' for a greater margin of safety .<br>
The area was covered with deep undergrowth, Tall elephant grass, banana trees and long vines that stretched out and crossed the narrow trail I was following. To my right waist high elephant grass was intermixed with several clusters of palm trees and tall bamboo stalks. <br><br>
As I came around a turn in the narrow trail I was following, a clear sense of danger became present. The area reeked with the smell of sweat, gook sweat, I could smell their presence, the smell of hot spices. Danger was near, very near and something was going to happen and happen soon. <br>
 <br>
I  was about to take a step forward when time stood still - it really stood still. I had been walking forward but was now looking at my left leg that appeared to be stuck in midair. It wasn't moving forward and I'm thinking to myself, this is odd. <br>
&quot;Why isn't my foot moving forward? Why is it taking so long for it to come down?<br>
I remembered the silence all around me. A unique silence as if I had entered another dimension, a dimension without sound, without smells, without life, without time. Only my mind was functioning everything else in the world had stopped. My breathing had stopped, my heart stood still, but my mind was taking in, all at once a panoramic view of the whole area, and this conscience of this awareness scared me, and I wondered if I was dead. <br>
I then heard the impossible, to my right I heard the hammer moving forward and striking the primer of a live round. I heard the primer ignite the powder that exploded inside the bullets casing. I heard the noise the bullet made as the rifling turned the bullet clockwise inside the barrel as it made its way forward. <br>
At the same time I heard the exploding sound the bullet made as it cleared the machine gun's barrel, I felt two strong hands grab me from behind, from the top of my shoulders they pulled me backwards. <br>
In that millisecond, time caught up with me and I saw my feet fly out from under me. As I flew backwards twelve rounds of automatic machine gun fire shattered the palm tree that was in a direct line of where I would have been standing had my foot continued to carry me forward. <br><br>
I hit the ground with my back so hard that I bounced off its surface. The M16 rifle I had been carrying had flown out of my hands and landed over to my right. I scrambled to get to it as our right flank exploded with carbine, machine gun and automatic AK47 fire. Grenades exploded up and down the trail and out toward our right front. We were in an ambush and I was smack in the middle of the kill zone with incoming fire coming in from in front of me and from our right front. I turned to my right to see who had grabbed me from behind as I reached out and grabbed hold of the M16, and released the safety.   There was no one there.  Murphy the new men in 2nd squad was flat on his stomach crawling toward me from about 35 feet away. <br>
When he saw that I was moving, he stopped, turned and returned fire. The enemy's incoming fire power was intense, it was coming in thick and fast, grenades and claymore mines were exploding all along the trail for about 100 feet directly in front of us and the majority of it was all incoming. A few minutes later it was all over it had ended just as quickly as it had started.<br><br>
When the air cleared I crawled over to where Murphy was, to thank him for pulling me out of harms way. His eyes opened wide as I drew near. <br>
&quot;Hey, Murphy thanks for pulling me back.&quot; <br>
&quot;I didn't pull you back, You're not hurt? He asked.<br>
&quot;No, you pulled me back, don't you remember, how'd you know they were there?<br>
&quot;I didn't pull you back, I saw the bullets hit the tree to your left about the same time I saw you flying backwards. I thought you were a goner with that many rounds hitting all around you. That's what I thought had thrown you backwards. I though that you had been hit by that first volley of bullets, I didn't think you were alive. I was crawling over to see how bad you were hurt when I saw you moving.&quot; <br>
I realized that he wasn't lying, he wasn't near me when the fire fight started, I remembered that seconds after the first rounds were fired that he was flat on the ground to far away to have been the one to have pulled me back. I remember wondering how he had gotten so far away from me in such a short time. But if it wasn't him that pulled me back, who did? <br><br>

